Section B — Work & Recent Onboarding 
[09:00] Interviewer: What did the first days or weeks look like? 
[09:30] Participant P01: My first week was a mix of excitement and confusion. I had access to many tools — Jira, Confluence, GitHub, internal AI dashboards — but no clear sequence of what to do first. I received a lot of documents, but none were prioritized. I spent most of the first week trying to understand the team structure and where information lived. 
[10:00] Interviewer: Top 3 things you need to know? 
[10:30] Participant P01: The codebase architecture and how services were documented. The AI capabilities the company already had, so I didn't reinvent anything. Who the decision-makers were for engineering and AI-related features. 
[11:00] Interviewer: Hardest part of getting started? Why? 
[11:30] Participant P01: The hardest part was understanding the workflow between engineering, product, and the AI team. Everyone used different tools, and documentation wasn't centralized. I had to ask multiple people to confirm whether something was up to date. 
[12:00] Interviewer: Did onboarding feel helpful or box ticking? 
[12:30] Participant P01: It felt like box ticking. HR modules were generic and didn't explain how the product teams actually, I worked. There was no personalized onboarding for engineers or AI-focused roles. 
 
 
Section C — Finding Information at Work 
[13:00] Interviewer: Where do you go first when you need an answer? 
[13:30] Participant P01: I usually start with Confluence. If I don't find it there, I check Teams or ask someone directly. For code-related info, check out GitHub first. 
[14:00] Interviewer: How often do you check out more than one place? What's annoying? 
[14:30] Participant P01: Almost every day. The annoying part is that different teams store information differently. Engineering uses Confluence; some teams use GitHub wikis, and products use Google Drive. There's no single source of truth. 
[15:00 Interviewer: Tell me about a time when you couldn't find something important. 
[15:30] Participant P01: I needed the latest AI model for API documentation. The version in Confluence was outdated, and the updated one was hidden in a private Teams chat. I wasted nearly an hour searching. 
[16:00] Interviewer: How do you keep track of important links or documents? 
[16:30] Participant P01: I bookmark things and create personal folders, but it becomes messy. I also pin messages in teams, but after a few weeks, it's impossible to remember what's pinned where. 
[17:00] Interviewer: If you had one home screen at work, what would you want to show? 
[17:30] Participant P01: My tasks, deadlines, code repositories, AI model updates, and key documents. Also, a “recent changes” feed so I know what's new. 
[18:00] Interviewer: What information should be quick to reach? 
[18:30] Participant P01: API documentation updates, project requirements, and AI model behavior guidelines. These should be accessible within seconds. 
[19:00] Interviewer: How do you know if a document is correct or up to date? 
[19:30] Participant P01: I usually ask someone. There's no reliable indicator in most tools. That's a big problem. 
 
Section D — Starting a Job / Smart Onboarding 
[20:00] Interviewer: What would have made you feel less lost on Day 1? 
[20:30] Participant P01: A personalized onboarding dashboard for engineers — showing the tools I need, the codebase overview, the AI guidelines, and the first tasks to complete. 
[21:00] Interviewer: Did you know what to do next each day? 
[21:30] Participant P01: Not really. I had to ask my manager frequently. A daily or weekly onboarding plan would have helped a lot. 
[22:00] Interviewer: What makes onboarding feel personal and useful? 
[22:30] Participant P01: Role-specific content. Engineers need different onboarding than designers or HR. Also, interactive onboarding — not just documents. 
[23:00] Interviewer: What made you feel “I'm on track”? 
[23:30] Participant P01: When I completed small tasks and got feedback. Also, when I understood how the AI models worked and how my code contributed to them. 
[24:00] Interviewer: When you needed help, did you know who to ask? 
[24:30] Participant P01: Not at first. I didn't know who owned what. A “who to ask” directory would have helped. 
 
Section E — AI Helper Trust 
[25:00] Interviewer: Have you used AI tools at work? 
[25:30] Participant P01: Yes — for generating code snippets, summarizing documents, and analyzing bug reports. AI is helpful, but it needs transparency. 
[26:00] Interviewer: What would make you trust an AI answer? 
[26:30] Participant P01: Clear sources, reasoning, and confidence levels. I want to know why the AI suggested something. 
[27:00] Interviewer: What would make you not trust it? 
[27:30] Participant P01: If it gives vague answers or doesn't show evidence. Also, if it contradicts known guidelines. 
[28:00] Interviewer: What questions should AI redirect to a human? 
[28:30] Participant P01: Anything involving HR, performance, conflict, or sensitive decisions. Also, anything that requires emotional judgement. 
[29:00] Interviewer: Would you worry about privacy? What would reassure you? 
[29:30] Participant P01: Yes. I'd want clear documentation on what data the AI uses, how it stores it, and whether personal data is excluded. 
 
